<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="92" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="92">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Barkworthia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Barkworthia stillmanii" order="Poales" pageId="3" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stillmanii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="92">Barkworthia stillmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in scattered locations in northern California (Butte, El Dorado, Nevada, Placer, Plumas, Sacramento, Shasta, Sierra, Tehama, Trinity, Tulare, and Yuba Counties) associated with yellow pine and red fir forests; 10-1500 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">Barkworth 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Calflora" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C." pageId="20" pageNumber="109" publicationUrl="https://www.calflora.org/" refId="B5" refString="Calflora, 2018. Information on California plants for education, research and conservation. Berkeley, California: The Calflora Database (a non-profit organization). https://www.calflora.org/" title="Information on California plants for education, research and conservation. Berkeley, California: The Calflora Database (a non-profit organization)." url="https://www.calflora.org/" year="2018">Calflora 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="93" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="93" start="start">Comments</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="93">
In a molecular-derived phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Barkworthia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="tribe" tribe="Stipeae">Stipeae</taxonomicName>
using 10 DNA markers 
<taxonomicName authority="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng, 2019" authorityName="K.Romaschenko, P.M.Peterson &amp; R.J.Soreng" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Barkworthia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Barkworthia stillmanii" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stillmanii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Barkworthia stillmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sister to a well-supported 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Gramineae" genus="Piptatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Piptatherum" order="Poales" pageId="4" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="93">Piptatherum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade, which is strictly Old World in distribution, and has cauducous awns, and dark glossy lemmas in fruit (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">Romaschenko et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
